node.text:
Just like consumer cars have to undergo crash testing, so do commercial semitrucks. While some of these tests are the same that production cars undergo, others are designed specifically for trucks. 

Thanks to trucking companies like Volvo and Scania as well as the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety, safety standards for these trucks are only improving.

node.text: Vietnamese woodworker Truong Van Dao built a fully drivable wooden Bugatti. It’s one third the size of an actual car, but a near replica of the luxury automaker’s $8.9 million Centodieci hypercar. We explore how he did the entire project in just 40 days.

node.title: How to build a fully drivable wooden Bugatti

node.text: A wave of upcoming hypercars claim to accelerate 0 to 60 mph in as little as 1.7 seconds. However, nothing has been verified. The reality is that no production car has ever managed an official 0 to 60 time of under 2 seconds. There's a reason for that. We break down how current technology has created that limit, and what could be done to break it.

node.title: Why going 0 to 60 mph in under 2 seconds is almost impossible

node.text:
In 2019, the Bugatti Chiron Super Sport 300  became the first production car to drive 300 mph. This was almost 15 years after the Bugatti Veyron became the first to reach 250. So why did it take so long for automakers to build a car just 50 mph faster? We explore what makes 300 mph such a difficult benchmark to reach and what automakers like Bugatti have been doing to chase it.

#cars #speed #bugatti #sportscar

node.title: Why It's Almost Impossible For Cars To Go 300 Miles Per Hour

node.text:
Amazon told employees it plans to stop offering onsite COVID-19 tests for its warehouse workers on July 30, The Information reported Monday.

In a note sent to employees, Amazon said past safety measures had put the company on a "path to normal" and that "free COVID-19 testing is now widely available and our employees have many options available to them, including through health providers and public testing sites."

Amazon first rolled out a pilot of its testing program around May 2020, eventually expanding it to around 650 locations in November as case counts rose.

Amazon told Insider it's starting to scale back testing because of the progress it had observed among its workforce and the general public. It said that it's continuing to evaluate temporary safety measures rolled out during the pandemic to ensure they're aligned with guidance from public health officials. It added that it's prepared to resume testing as needed.

Read more of Tyler Sonnemaker's story at the link in our bio.

(Credit: Getty Images)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo showing Jeff Bezos in Blue Origin's New Shepard rocket with the headline, "If Jeff Bezos' rocket fails during launch, an emergency system should jettison him to safety".

node.text:
Jeff Bezos, his brother, an 82-year-old aviator, and a Dutch teen are launching to space on Tuesday. They'll fly on Blue Origin's New Shepard rocket, which is well tested, but spaceflight is always risky. If the rocket fails, an emergency escape system should jettison the passengers to safety.

Click the link in bio to read more.

Only 17% of electronic waste is recycled. That’s because devices aren’t designed to be recycled. They’re full of tiny, toxic materials that are hard and expensive to break down.

But if extracted safely, those materials could mean big money for e-recyclers like Sims Lifecycle Services. 

We visited Sims’ Tennessee recycling facility to find out why e-waste is getting harder to deal with.

Click the link in our bio to watch the full video.

node.text:
Xiaomi has overtaken Apple to become the second-biggest smartphone seller in the world.

For the first time, the Chinese electronics giant took second place in Canalys' quarterly smartphone sales report, with a 17% share of the market.

Ben Stanton, research manager at Canalys, said: "All vendors are fighting hard to secure component supply amid global shortages, but Xiaomi already has its sights set on the next prize: displacing Samsung to become the world's largest vendor."

Click the link in our bio to read the full story by Grace Dean.

(Credit: Canalys Smartphone Analysis, July 2021)

node.text:
Between January 2014 and August 2015, the company fired 52 employees over exploiting user data for personal means, said an advance copy of "An Ugly Truth: Inside Facebook's Battle for Domination" that Insider obtained.

One Facebook engineer abused employee access to user data to track down a woman who had left him after they fought.

The engineer, who is unnamed, tapped into the data to "confront" a woman with whom he had been vacationing in Europe after she left the hotel room they had been sharing, the book said. He was able to figure out her location at a different hotel.

Another Facebook engineer used his employee access to dig up information on a woman with whom he had gone on a date after she stopped responding to his messages.

Click the link in our bio to read the complete story.

(Credit: Getty Images)

node.text:
A New York couple continues to negotiate fees and contracts with Telsa over the solar panels they had on their Hudson Valley home. 

The California-based electronic car company also produces solar panels.  However, Jamie Fedorko and Sabrina Ferrer say that their Telsa panels led to continuous leaks in their roof and mold levels 10 times the healthy limit. 

While Tesla removed the solar panels and the couple fixed their house, Fedorko and Ferrer continue to battle Tesla on fees and their contract.

Click the link in our bio to read more of Isobel Asher Hamilton's story. 

(Credit: Tesla; Bill Pugliano/Getty Images; Samantha Lee/Insider)

An unopened Nintendo Super Mario 64 game cartridge sold for a record-breaking $1.56 million at auction on Sunday by Heritage Auctions. According to the Verge, it's now the most expensive game in the world. 

The Super Mario 64 game — Mario's first 3D adventure — was released in 1996. On Heritage Auction's website, the starting price for the near-mint video cartridge game was $19. The identity of the buyer has not been made public.

The $1.56 million sale marks the third time the record for the world's most expensive game has been broken in 2021 alone.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo of Virgin Galactic spacecraft with headline 'Tom Hanks, Leonardo DiCaprio, Justin Bieber, and Lady Gaga all reserved $250,000 tickets to fly to space with Virgin Galactic'

node.text:
Roughly 600 people from 58 countries have reserved tickets worth up to $250,000 to be in the first waves of space tourists, according to company filings. 

The list of stars who bought tickets, according to USA Today, includes, includes celebrities like Leonardo DiCaprio, Tom Hanks, Brad Pitt, Angelina Jolie, Russell Brand, Lady Gaga, Katy Perry, Justin Bieber, and Ashton Kutcher.

Virgin Galactic says it aims to launch as many as 400 flights per year, carrying up to six passengers and two pilots each, departing from and landing at the Spaceport America home base in New Mexico. Former CEO George Whitesides told Insider he expects space tourism to eventually pull in $10 to $15 billion per year.

Click the link in bio to read the full story by Dominick Reuter.

(Credit: Virgin Galactic)
